    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Impact of Foreign Direct Investment on Passenger Car Segment in India</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Rajalakshmi.K</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Direct Investment<br />Car Segment</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Aug-2013 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0130</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">FDI Inflows to Automobile Industry have been at an increasing rate as India
has witnessed a major economic liberalization over the years in terms of various
industries. The basic advantages provided by India in the automobile sector include,
advanced technology, cost-effectiveness, and efficient manpower. Besides, India has
a well-developed and competent Auto Ancillary Industry along with automobile
testing and R&amp;D centers. The automobile sector in India ranks third in
manufacturing three wheelers and second in manufacturing of two wheelers. The
major investing countries are Mauritius (mainly routed from developed countries),
USA, Japan, UK, Germany, the Netherlands and South Korea.
The FDI in Automobile Industry has experienced huge growth in the past few
years. The increase in the demand for cars and other vehicles is powered by the
increase in the levels of disposable income in India. The options have increased with
quality products from foreign car manufacturers. However, the growing world
market and domestic market lives scope for future expansion and introduction of
domestic manufacturing facility in India and in Mexico for the automobile products
by means of joint venture. In order to further improve the automobiles in the Indian
domestic market, to provide world class facilities of automotive testing and
certification and to ensure a healthy competition among the manufacturers at a level
playing field, ministry has undertaken to lay down the road map for future
development of the industry in the form of ‘Automotive Mission Plan 2006-2016’.
Developing countries compete to attract FDI and therefore it has become
pertinent to understand the factors that influence the flow of investment into the
country. It is generally assumed that FDI will have a positive impact on the economy
of the host country and this assumption requires empirical verification.
Existing literature survey with a view to highlight the basic research issue for
this study. The review of literature proves beneficial in identifying the research
issues and the research gaps, which are mainly the edifices on which the objectives
of the present study are based on. This study about Foreign Direct Investments in
India analyzes about the trends and patterns of foreign direct investment flow into the
country.
Consumers are very important part of the survival of the Motor Vehicle
manufacturing industry. The primary data were collected between January 2012 and
August 2012 collected from passenger car owners, travel partners and franchised car
dealers with access to customer databases of varied foreign brands. The present study
not only analyses the customer satisfaction of the foreign made passenger car, but
also to explore the relationship between Customer satisfaction, Customer Loyalty
and Word of mouth (WOM) Communication in the passenger car segment in India.
The framework of this study was developed based on American Customer
Satisfaction Index by Claes Fornell and et al (1996) which represent new type of
customer based measurement system for evaluating-and enhancing-the performance
of firms by production of passenger cars and thereby measuring national economies.
The brands like BMW, Mercedes Benz, Volkswagen, Maruthi Suzuki,
Hyundai and Fiat. The variables used are Perceived Quality, Perceived Value,
customer Loyalty, Customer Satisfaction and customer expectation. The purpose of
this study is to identify the relationship between FDI Investments in the above
mentioned companies, customer satisfaction and its antecedents and consequences.
Analytical and Empirical research to find the result from the studies using secondary
data, the researcher using three statistical tool for analyzing the study, ARIMA,
Linear and Compound Model for analysis to measure future prediction using time
series analysis.
According to our Hypothesis, Structural Equation Model was developed to
assess the statistical significance of the proposed relationships between overall
Customer satisfaction and its dimensions. Factor Analysis was applied to the
responses obtained from Passenger Car owners on various aspects related to
customer satisfaction and expectation
The aggregate results of the select FDI companies in 2008-09 revealed that
the global financial crisis during the year had a significant impact on the performance
of the non-government, non-financial, FDI companies. Financial performance of
passenger car companies growth rate of sales, value of production and income
moderated, gross profit, profit after tax and profit retained declined in 2008-09 when
compared to those in 2007-08.
From the above result, it is concluded that there is significant relationship
between FDI inflow to Automobile Industries sales and revenue in Passenger vehicle
production.
In September 2011 petrol rates and interests rates are high for loans, buyers
are likely to go for diesel cars for their running cost. The inter correlation between
all the variables Customer Loyalty, Perceived Quality, Customer Expectation,
Perceived Value and Customer Satisfaction were significant and positive. Hence,
Word of Mouth Activity and Word of Mouth Praise might affect Customer
satisfaction by influencing Customer Loyalty there by select Car Brand. The results
provided strong support for all the variables which indicates, positive and direct role
of all the variables affecting customer satisfaction. Therefore, it was concluded that
they did not have a direct significant influence on Brand of Cars and Customer
Satisfaction.
Demand for diesel vehicles has increased so much that it has more than made
up for the fall in demand for petrol vehicles. For the Indian automobile industry in
achieving the National Vision would primarily consist of developing a supply base in
terms of technical and human capabilities, achieving economies of scale and
lowering manufacturing costs, overcoming infrastructural bottlenecks, stimulating
domestic demand and exploiting export and international business opportunities.
Hence, performance measurement in all type of foreign made cars like
Lamborghini, in all over the world and fuel efficiency for some special types of
brand cars should be considered in future research. The research study measured the
Customer Satisfaction and Customer expectation of foreign made passenger cars,
limited to some of the car owners in India. Hence, there is a scope to expand the
study in all the cities in India, to avoid the significant regional gaps in consumer’s
attitude.</td></tr>
